We have the equation $\frac{2x-1}{2x+2}=\frac{x-3}{x-1}$. Cross-multiplying and simplifying, we get \begin{align*}
(2x-1)(x-1)&=(2x+2)(x-3)\\
2x^2 - x - 2x + 1 &= 2x^2 + 2x - 3 \cdot 2x - 3 \cdot 2 \\
2x^2 - 3x + 1&=2x^2-4x-6\\
x&=\boxed{-7}
\end{align*}

We have the system of equations:

\begin{align*}
x + y &= 153 \\
\frac{x}{y} &= 0.7 \\
\end{align*}

From the second equation, multiplying both sides by $y$ gives $x=.7y$. Next, substituting the second equation into the first to eliminate $x$ gives $.7y+y=153$, or $y=90$. Plugging in this value into the first equation in the original system of equations gives $x+90=153$ or $x=63$. Thus, $y-x=90-63=\boxed{27}$.

problem:
If $f(x)$, whose graph is shown below, is defined on $1 \le x \le 6$, what is the maximum value of $f^{-1}(x)$? [asy]

